a 10-minute board game for two players
EQUIPMENT:
WINNING
STRATEGY:
Start by scattering markers around, then
connect them into chains. Pairs of markers
adjacent to the same two spaces are
hard to block!
HISTORY:
This game was invented by Piet Hein
in 1942. Grahm Nash also claimed to have
invented it a few years later, but when most
people claim to have invented something that
someone else has already invented,
we call that “not having invented it.”
You will need two sets of up to 61 markers each.
Usually, 20 will be plenty.
HOW TO PLAY:
Start by choosing two sides, A or B.
Players take turns putting one of their
markers in any unoccupied hexagon.
Once placed, the markers do not move.
Use your markers to a chain of adjacent markers
that connect hexes on opposite edges of the board.
